content.text:
*"He shot his arrows and scattered the enemy, with 
great bolts of lightning he routed them."*{Psalm 18:14}{The path of a 
projectile, unimpeded by the air, would be an exact parabola.}{Galileo Galilei}

content.solution:
From $x^2 = 12y$, we have $4p = 12$, so $p = 3$.

Key features:

- Vertex: $(0, 0)$

- Focus: $(0, 3)$

- Directrix: $y = -3$

- Latus rectum length: $|4p| = 12$

The latus rectum passes through the focus $(0, 3)$, horizontally. Its 
length is 12, so it extends 6 units on each side of the focus. The 
endpoints are $(-6, 3)$ and $(6, 3)$.

center
tikzpicture[scale=0.4]
 % Axes
 (-8,0) – (8,0) node[right] {$x$};
 (0,-4) – (0,8) node[above] {$y$};

 % Grid
 in {-6,-4,-2,2,4,6}
 (,0.1) – (,-0.1) node[below] { $\x$};
 in {-2,2,4,6}
 (0.1,) – (-0.1,) node[left] { $\y$};

 % Parabola

 plot (, {/12});

 % Focus
 lldraw[AtlasTeal] (0,3) circle (4pt);
 at (1,3.5) {$F$};

 % Directrix
 (-7,-3) – (7,-3);
 at (8,-3) {$y=-3$};

 % Latus rectum
 (-6,3) – (6,3);
 lldraw[AtlasWarm] (-6,3) circle (3pt);
 lldraw[AtlasWarm] (6,3) circle (3pt);

 % Vertex
 lldraw (0,0) circle (3pt);
tikzpicture
center

The parabola passes through the vertex $(0, 0)$ and through the endpoints 
of the latus rectum, $(-6, 3)$ and $(6, 3)$.
